6/7 The crucial question is, can technology fix this? Not in and by itself. It depends on whether there is enough awareness to drive streamlined pressure for change, rather than blind rage. Given the environmental and other issues all this has created, time is of essence.

5/7 The reasoning for those policies is that giving a select few breaks is a good thing for everyone, as it will drive economy & society forward, and the inequality this will inevitably create does not matter. The trickle down, rising tide argument. This is a fallacy.

4/7 This has made the appropriation of productivity even greater. Where does this additional value go, expressed in terms of financial gain? Employers, corporations, rentiers. This has been exacerbated by specific policies instated after the 70s.

3/7 That average office job in the 70s would probably get workers their own house. Today that's a dream for most. That must say something about whether the productivity gap is real. Factors such as mobility, work market pressure and the gig economy have expanded working hours.

2/7 Let's take an average office job, a marketing rep for example. The increase in productivity between the 70s and now is incredible - think word processors, spreadsheets, marketing automation etc. And yes, that rep is probably expected to reply to messages off working hours too
1/7 That's essentially a political economy discussion. What we're talking about are things such as wage - productivity gap, abstract vs concrete labour (aka 'work vs labour'), etc. Bear with me.

6/ So back to your question, if your chatbot can be trained with federated learning with data never leaving users' devices and run locally to be personalised to you, we're starting to get somewhere :)

5/ Decentralised systems doing anything at all with AI/ML need this. At @OVioHQ we're therefore pushing the envelope on these kinds of technologies, amongst others in our research programme with @imperialcollege led by @nud3l_ .

4/ Some promising approaches are advances in homomorphic encryption (still slow, but improving), differential privacy (used by FANGs already) and federated machine learning (surprisingly spearheaded by Google https:// ai.googleblog.com/2017/04/federa ted-learning-collaborative.html?m=1 … ).

3/ Another interesting question is about training AI. If the best AIs are trained with lots and lots of data, how can we _train_ models without creating huge centrally controlled data silos?
2/ This is very different from common approaches to bots (or any web app really), but decentralised architectures are beginning to make these kinds of things possible.

1/ One approach is don't let the data come to the compute (the big bad corporate owned data center) but let (part of) the compute come to the data. If parts of the bot dealing with sensitive data can run locally, your sensitive data never needs to leave the device.
